  <h2>How Does Red Light Therapy Improve Skin Over Time?</h2>
  <p>
    Red light therapy (specifically wavelengths between 600–700 nm and near-infrared at 700–1100 nm) works by stimulating mitochondrial energy production in skin cells. This triggers the production of collagen and elastin, proteins essential for skin firmness and elasticity. The mechanism is well-documented in clinical research.
  </p>
  <p>
    The results are gradual: you won't see changes after one session. But with consistent 10–20 minute sessions, 3–5 times per week, you'll notice improvements in 4–8 weeks. Fine lines soften, acne reduces, and skin texture improves.
  </p>
